00:02:19.430 --> 00:02:24.030
Our work began more than 20
years ago when Luz Santana and I

00:02:24.030 --> 00:02:27.490
and several other people were
working in Lawrence, Massachusetts.

00:02:27.490 --> 00:02:32.830 position:64%
And we learned from parents, that we were
working on dropout prevention program.

00:02:32.830 --> 00:02:38.040 position:72%
And our role was to try to engage more parents
to participate in their children's education.

00:02:38.040 --> 00:02:42.980 position:73%
And the parents told us, we don't go to the
schools because we don't even know what to ask.

00:02:42.980 --> 00:02:45.450 position:63%
So we thought we had a solution to that.

00:02:45.450 --> 00:02:47.100 position:66%
We could come up with a list of questions.

00:02:47.100 --> 00:02:51.150 position:63%
But what they actually named was a more
fundamental problem, is that the ability

00:02:51.150 --> 00:02:54.750 position:61%
to ask one's own questions, to know how
to organize your thinking around things

00:02:54.750 --> 00:02:58.960 position:63%
that you're not familiar with, that you
don't know, is really the key challenge.

00:02:58.960 --> 00:03:05.350 position:67%
So what we really needed to do was relaying
to look at how do we teach that skill.

00:03:05.350 --> 00:03:10.960 position:73%
So we began our work, working with parents, and
ASCD recently published a book on our strategy

00:03:10.960 --> 00:03:15.290 position:63%
for working with parents to get them
more involved as partners with educators

00:03:15.290 --> 00:03:18.490
and in children's education, we
also began to work in healthcare

00:03:18.490 --> 00:03:23.470 position:67%
and we saw a National Institute's of Health
Study that showed a doubling and tripling

00:03:23.470 --> 00:03:28.280 position:66%
